- Concurrency fix is coherent. `commit_gate` serializes the full projection commit body, the threshold-crossing row does `add -> count -> take` under the accumulator lock, the pin transaction updates `mean_vec` and re-quantizes all committed rows in the same tx, and later rows center on insert. I do not see an interleaving that leaves a row permanently uncentered or allows a double-pin. Refs: `src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/src/lib.rs:174`, `src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/src/lib.rs:3533`, `src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/src/lib.rs:3565`, `src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/src/lib.rs:3620`, `src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/src/lib.rs:3682`

- Locking looks ordered, not cyclic. The new path takes `commit_gate -> mean_accumulator -> SQLite tx`, and I did not find any inverse path that takes `mean_accumulator` or state locks and then waits on `commit_gate`. State cleanup remains outside the commit gate. Refs: `src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/src/lib.rs:174`, `src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/src/lib.rs:3079`, `src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/src/lib.rs:3533`

- `catch_unwind` addresses the scheduler wedge. On panic, the batch is marked terminal as `ProjectionPanic`, `active_jobs`/`in_flight` cleanup still runs unconditionally, and the same cursors are not re-enqueued into an infinite loop. Reuse of the worker connection is acceptable on this code path: embedder panics happen before SQL, and commit-path panics unwind the local tx before reuse. Refs: `src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/src/lib.rs:3120`, `src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/src/lib.rs:3134`, `src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/src/lib.rs:3177`, `src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/src/lib.rs:3656`

- Recovery pin is idempotent and runs before workers exist. `open_locked` conditionally repairs only `MC-required && mean_vec NULL && rows >= threshold`, sets the open report pinned flag, and only then does `ProjectionRuntime::new` decide whether to allocate a live accumulator and spawn workers. Refs: `src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/src/lib.rs:1473`, `src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/src/lib.rs:1511`, `src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/src/lib.rs:488`, `src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/src/lib.rs:519`, `src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/src/lib.rs:3694`

- Truncation matches the locked BGE contract. The tokenizer is configured with `with_truncation(max_length=512)` before `encode(input, true)`, so specials stay tokenizer-managed rather than being sliced off manually. The added test exercises a >512-token document and asserts success at dim 384. Refs: `src/rust/crates/fathomdb-embedder/src/candle_bge.rs:50`, `src/rust/crates/fathomdb-embedder/src/candle_bge.rs:114`, `src/rust/crates/fathomdb-embedder/src/candle_bge.rs:160`, `src/rust/crates/fathomdb-embedder/tests/candle_bge.rs:130`, `dev/design/embedder-decision.md:117`

- I did not see regression to the existing retrieval/write contracts. The search path still uses the same `TOP_K_BIT_CANDIDATES = 192`, cursor advancement still happens after terminal-state recording, and the `write_vector_for_test` pin block is unchanged. Refs: `src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/src/lib.rs:2140`, `src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/src/lib.rs:2744`, `src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/src/lib.rs:2932`, `src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/src/lib.rs:3682`

- EU-7 reporting is honest. The harness explicitly says it does not re-pin the 0.90 floor or K, uses same-model f32 ground truth, excludes the target from both GT and production, mirrors the AC budgets, and the output JSON plainly reports `0.828 < 0.90` with `R - 2*sigma = 0.795 -> 0.79`. I did not see floor gerrymandering or quiet budget relaxation. Refs: `src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/tests/eu7_real_corpus_ac.rs:24`, `src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/tests/eu7_real_corpus_ac.rs:35`, `src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/tests/eu7_real_corpus_ac.rs:123`, `src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/tests/eu7_real_corpus_ac.rs:399`, `src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/tests/eu7_real_corpus_ac.rs:701`, `src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/tests/eu7_real_corpus_ac.rs:731`, `dev/plans/runs/0.7.1-EU-7-output.json:31`, `dev/plans/runs/0.7.1-EU-7-output.json:37`, `dev/plans/runs/0.7.1-EU-7-output.json:45`, `dev/plans/runs/0.7.1-EU-7-output.json:55`

- The shipped choices still match `embedder-decision.md`: `bge-small`, dim `384`, truncation `512`, no silent recompute policy, and K locked at `192`. The new open-time repair is a crash-recovery exception, not a general recompute-on-open policy. Refs: `dev/design/embedder-decision.md:55`, `dev/design/embedder-decision.md:117`, `dev/design/embedder-decision.md:232`, `dev/design/embedder-decision.md:297`

## Reviewer process notes

Reviewed the range diff-first as requested: commit list, full read of `dev/plans/runs/0.7.1-EU-7-findings.md` and `dev/plans/runs/0.7.1-EU-7-output.json`, then targeted `git diff` / `git show` / small `sed` windows for `lib.rs`, `candle_bge.rs`, and the new focused tests.

One minor note I did not score as a concern: the EU-7 JSON metadata writes `"rerank_k_locked": 192` directly rather than reading the engine constant, but the measured path itself goes through `engine.search()` and therefore uses the live `TOP_K_BIT_CANDIDATES` value at runtime.
